<html>
<head>
<title>About the SBSC</title>
</head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF">
<img src="/sbsc/sbsmall.gif">
<p>
<center>
<h2>The Small Business Survival Committee</h2>
<P>
<hr size="4" width="45%"> 
<a href="/sbsc/membership.html.cgi">Joining SBSC</a>
<P>
<a href="/sbsc/pubs.html">Publications</a>
<p>
<a href="/sbsc/kerrigan.html">Who Is Karen Kerrigan?</a>
<hr size="4" width="45%">  
</center>
<p>
<blockquote>
Small business drives America's economy.  By 1996, 8 out of 10 jobs in America will be generated by small business.  Yet, too often the United States government ignores this reality and creates an environment hostile to small business creation.
                 <P>
Between 1989 and 1992, government regulations on small business increased over 34%.  By 1992, small businesses were burdened with nearly $130 billion more in costs in 1990.  Increased government regulations and higher taxes have added billions more in costs to small business operations.
     <P>
With great peril to the United States' competitiveness, legislators mandate costly, ineffectual, and punitive regulations that undermine individual freedom to control their own livelihood.  SBSC works to eliminate the burdensome and unnecessary tax and regulatory demands on small business.  Our goal is to amend current punitive policies to policies that preserve and enhance the entrepreneurial spirit.
        <P>
You can be certain that we always fight for principle; too much is at stake in America.
<P>
For more information send  e-mail to <a href="mailto:rstikes@sbsc.org"> Renee Stikes</a> at rstikes@sbsc.org.<p>

</blockquote>
