<html><head><title>VOTE AMERICA:  Conventions</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>

<P>
<h2>Conventions</h2>
</center><P>
In a sense, the national conventions are giant ads for the parties,
huge 4-day television spots.  Although they formerly served as
decision-making bodies, the party conventions have become more
like coronations.  Seeking to convey unity and harmony to the
television audience, party officials work to resolve or paper
over differences in advance of the convention.  The result is
a dearth of news.
<P>
<center><a href="convent.jpg"><img src="convent.gif" alt="Timeline" border="0"></a></center>
<P>
Despite their reduced role, conventions are not just meetings
of people with silly hats; they continue to fulfill a number of
important functions.  They provide a venue for party activists
from across the country to get reacquainted and do some networking.
 The diverse interest groups that make up a party's constituency
are represented, and each tries to get its individual message
out.  Fundraisers congregate at various receptions, luncheons,
and dinners.  Attracted by the presence of 15,000 media representatives
from across the country and around the world, other groups try
to grab a few seconds of air time or lines of print.  
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Hosting a party convention provides a big economic boost to a
city, and there is spirited competition for the privilege.  The
Democratic National Committee announced its selection of Chicago
in August 1994; the convention will be held at the United Center
from August 26-29. Republicans announced their choice, San Diego,
in January 1995; their convention will unfold at the San Diego
Convention Center on August 12.  
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The money to put on the major party conventions comes largely
from the Presidential Election Campaign Fund, paid for by the
checkoff on Federal income tax forms.  (In 1992 the Democratic
and Republican National Conventions each received $11.4 million
from the U.S. Treasury; these numbers will be adjusted for inflation
in 1996.)  In addition, host committees in each city work with
volunteers and businesses to see that a proper welcome is given
to delegates and media personnel.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;One of the formalities of the convention is adoption of the party
platform.  In the months preceding the convention, the party conducts
a series of hearings at which various interest groups are given
the opportunity to express their views.  Then the platform is
drawn up.  As Theodore White observed in The Making of the President
1960, the final document is largely a rhetorical exercise.  White
wrote that, &quot;...in actual fact, all platforms are meaningless:
the program of either party is what lies in the vision and conscience
of the candidate the party chooses to lead it.&quot;  Nonetheless,
each campaign highlights the gross faults and glaring distortions
in the other party's platform.  In 1992 for example, the Clinton
campaign produced &quot;The 1992 Republican Platform: An Annotated
Version,&quot; while the Bush campaign came up with a &quot;Platform
Comparison--Faith in Individuals versus Faith in Government.&quot;
 
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A successful convention can provide a boost for the candidate
heading into the fall campaign (&quot;convention bounce&quot;),
while a divisive one can undermine morale in the field.
<P>
<b>Additional Resources:</b>
<ul>
--.  1995.  <I>National Party Conventions 1831-1992</I>.  Washington,
D.C.: Congressional Quarterly.
<P>
