<html><head><title>VOTE AMERICA:  The Rest of the Primaries</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>

<P>
<h2>The rest of the primaries</h2>
<small><a href="#dates">1996 Republican Primary Dates</a></small>
</center>
<P>
In the past, party elites controlled blocks of delegates and brokered
conventions determined the party nominees.  In 1960, for example,
John Kennedy competed in primaries in just two states -- Wisconsin
and West Virginia.  Following the tumultuous 1968 Democratic Convention,
however, the Democratic party instituted reforms designed to ensure
full participation and a fair reflection of presidential preferences.
 In many instances, Republican rules were changed by default as
the Democratic reforms were written into state election codes.
 As a result of the changes, presidential preference primaries
have proliferated as the major way of selecting delegates to the
national conventions.
<P>
<center><a href="primarie.jpg"><img src="primarie.gif" border="0" alt="Timeline"></a></center>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Today the road to the nomination is a candidate-centered, <a href="images.html">media-driven
affair</a> that at times resembles a traveling circus.  Flinging the
candidates hither and yon across the country, the primary system
allows time for only the shallowest of campaigns in some states
(thereby requiring expensive media campaigns), and it leaves millions
of voters in late primaries with little say in the selection of
the nominees.  The 1996 primary season promises to be one of the
most frenetic ever.  Many states have moved the dates of their
primaries forward in an effort to have a greater say in the nominating
process.  
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Conventional wisdom suggests that the frontloaded, compressed
schedule could produce a Republican nominee by the end of March,
as 70 percent of the delegates will have been chosen by then.
 More remote scenarios postulate that none of the candidates will
achieve a majority of the delegates and the matter will have to
be decided at the convention.  Meanwhile, the Democratic primaries
are expected to be a mere formality.
<p>
Although this year's primaries will unfold so rapidly as to appear
a blur, there are certain highlights to look for and moments when
the momentum can shift.  States in some parts of the country have
scheduled their primaries on the same day, creating mini-regional
primaries: the March 5 Yankee primary, the March 12 Southern primary,
and the March 19 Rust Belt primary.  The Republican March 26 California
winner-take-all primary is an entity unto itself.  Finally, if
one of the candidates does wrap up the Republican nomination early,
the three or four months leading up to the convention will be
a pivotal period.
<P>
As chaotic as the primary season appears, there are rules.  At
the national level, the parties set broad rules that they hope
will result in a nominee who can win in November.  Within the
framework of the national rules and requirements of state election
codes, each state party sets its own rules for qualifying delegates
to the national conventions.  Meeting all the different states'
filing requirements poses a significant challenge to the campaigns.
 
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Republican rules for selecting delegates differ from those of
the Democrats in several important respects.  The Democratic party
has adopted an elaborate set of national rules, while Republican
rules allow the state parties more latitude in how they select
their delegates.  In a number of states such as California, Republicans
still use the winner-take-all system, a vestige of the old structure.
 
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The dominant method for selecting delegates is the primary.  Closed
primaries are restricted to registered party members.  In an open
primary, any registered voter can vote, so that members of one
party may try to influence the outcome of the other party's primary.
 In nonbinding, or beauty contest primaries, the delegates are
selected by other means. 
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Caucuses are a multistage process that starts in precinct or district
meetings and concludes with a state convention.  Caucuses require
more active involvement than do primaries.  Participants cannot
just take a quick trip to the polling booth; rather they must
be willing sit to through one or more meetings.  Candidates who
can effectively organize grassroots support often do well in caucuses,
but the system is used primarily in smaller states.
<P>
Turnout in presidential primaries is generally low.  The Committee
for the Study of the American Electorate, a nonpartisan, nonprofit
research organization based in Washington, found that in 1992
only 33,637,075 of 171,003,000 eligible Americans voted in the
presidential primaries, a 19.6 percent turnout.
<P>
The American system for choosing the party nominees is uniquely
convoluted.  Starting in the bleak winter landscapes of Iowa or
New Hampshire, candidates must put themselves through a grueling
four-month series of state primaries and caucuses.  The process
tests the candidates in many ways, including their ability to
raise money, deliver the same speech countless times, and look
good on television.  For those potential leaders not willing to
put themselves through these trials, there remains the option
of waging independent or third-party campaigns in the fall. However,
the Democratic and Republican nominations remain the surest path
to the White House.
<P>
<b>Additional Resources:</b>
<ul>
Steps to the Nomination.  C<I>ongressional Quarterly Weekly Special
Report.</I>  August 19, 1995, Volume 53, No. 33. An indispensable, state-by-state guide to the nominating process
with information on each state's political landscape, delegate
selection rules and past results.  (1-800-854-9043)
<P>
Robert D. Loevy.  1994.  The Flawed Path to the Presidency 1992:
Unfairness and Inequality in the Presidential Selection Process.
 Albany: State University Press of New York.
<P><a name="dates"></a>
