<html><head><title>VOTE AMERICA:  The Debates</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>

<P>
<h2>Debates</h2>
<small><a href="#points">Points to consider when watching a debate</a></small>
</center>
<P>
Perhaps the biggest event of the fall campaign is the series of
nationally televised presidential debates.  These first occurred
between Nixon and Kennedy in 1960, and they have been regular
fixtures since the Ford-Carter exchanges in 1976.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;While there is no requirement that the presidential candidates
meet, debates in the fall are almost inevitable because it will
likely harm a candidate if he or she is seen to be blocking them.
 The campaigns have the final word when it comes to the debates.
 Much posturing and intense negotiations take place as each campaign
strives to achieve the most favorable format and schedule.  
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Although the campaigns set the terms, there are other interested
parties.  First, there is the public.  How meaningful the debates
will be depends heavily on the rules arrived at through the campaigns'
negotiations.  A debate can reveal the candidates' positions and
their differences, or it can devolve into a scripted exercise
bordering on &quot;a joint press conference.&quot;  In 1992 the
Bush and Clinton camps agreed to allow Ross Perot to participate
in the debates, but the Libertarian candidate, who had qualified
for the ballot in all fifty states, was excluded.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The nonprofit Commission on Presidential Debates (CPD), established
in 1987, has emerged as the organizer of general election debates.
 The Commission is co-chaired by former heads of the Democratic
and Republican parties and is thus open to criticism.  Former
Rep. Tim Penny described it as &quot;a creature of the two major
parties.&quot;  In addition to the CPD, the networks and the League
of Women Voters have put forth credible debate proposals in recent
presidential elections.  
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In any event, the debates are high-stakes events.  Voters who
have not yet made up their minds can be won and lost depending
on what transpires.  The drama of direct confrontation attracts
an immense television audience.  In 1992, viewership for the three
presidential debates ranged from 85-97 million, and the vice-presidential
debate attracted 74 million viewers. 
<P>
<B>Additional Resources:</B>
<ul>
<a href="http://park.org/fair/Events/Debates">Commission on Presidential Debates</a><br>
601 Thirteenth Street, N.W.  Suite 310 South<br>
Washington, DC  20005<br>
phone:  (202) 872-1020   |  fax:  (202) 783-5923
  <P>
<ul>At this site, learn about the CPD's plans and how you can participate
in Debate Watch '96.</ul>
<P>
League of Women Voters Education Fund <br>
1730 M Street, N.W.<br>
Washington, DC  20036<br>
(202) 429-1965 
<P><ul>LWVEF publishes a 4-page pamphlet &quot;How to Watch a Debate.&quot;
 (Pub. #818).</ul>
<P>
Diana B. Carlin and Mitchell S. McKinney, eds.  1994.  T<I>he 1992
Presidential Debates in Focus</I>.  Westport, Conn.: Praeger Publishers.
</ul><P><a name="points"></a>
 <H3>Points to consider when watching a debate:</H3>
<P>
<ul><li>First, listen to the moderator explaining the format at
the outset of the debate.
<P>
<li>Who is the debate sponsor?
<P>
<li>Who is on the stage and who isn't; what criteria were used
to select participating candidates?
<P>
<li>Who asks the questions?  Is there a single moderator or
a panel?  Are the questioners network anchors, more obscure journalists,
non-journalists or even members of the audience?
<P>
<li>Is there a live audience and, if so, who is in it?  A live
audience and interruptions for applause can significantly change
the tempo of a debate.
<P>
<li>Is the subject matter confined to one area such as the economy,
or is it less focussed?
<P>
<li>What is the time limit, if any, on candidate responses and
rebuttals?  From one to two minutes is common.
<P>
<li>Is the set unobtrusive or does it distract?  What camera
angles are used and what are the most frequent shots?
<P>
<li>At the end of the debate, before the commentators tell you
what happened, write down your impressions.  What in your view
were the key moments and why were they important?  
<P>
<li>Finally, see how the media cover the debate, both in immediate
post-debate commentary and later in broadcast and print news.
 Frequent aspects of coverage are &quot;who won&quot; discussions
and reactions from voters.
</ul><P>
<br><center><small><a href="contents.html">Table of Contents</a> | <a href="elect.html">Next Section</a> | <a href="welcome.html">Vote America Home</a> | <a href="order.html.cgi">Order</a> | <a href="/townhall">Town Hall</a>
<P>
&copy; 1996 <a href="http://www.virtent.com">Virtual Entertainment</a></small>
</center>
