<html><head><title>VOTE AMERICA:  How Elections Work - Contents</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>

<P>
<h2>The transition period</h2>
</center><P>
As is taught in high school government classes, the president of the United States is not selected by direct popular vote, but by intermediaries known as electors.  The electoral system is outlined in the Twelfth Amendment to the Constitution, adopted in 1804, which significantly modified original provisions contained in Article II.  All told there are 538 electors.  The manner of selection of electors varies, but they are generally chosen by congressional district.  Each party presents a slate of electors, usually people with longstanding party ties.  In all states, with the exception of Maine and Nebraska, the winner of the popular vote takes all the electors.
<P>
<center><a href="trans.jpg"><img src="trans.gif" border="0" alt="Timeline"></a></center>
<P>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;The formal process of making the election official begins when governors in each state issue certificates of ascertainment which confirm the results and electors.  Then, on December 16, 1996, (the first Monday after the second Wednesday in December), electors will meet in each state capitol.  They will vote first for president and then for vice-president, and the vote will probably be unanimous.  Certificates of vote from each state are then sent to the United States Senate, where they are officially opened, counted, and ratified in early January.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;In the event that none of the candidates has a clear majority, the election goes into the House of Representatives.  This has only happened twice, most recently in 1824, although there was talk in June 1992 that a good showing by Ross Perot might throw the election into the House.  A second problem with the electoral system is that the popular vote winner can actually lose the election as a result of electoral math.  This last happened in the Hayes-Tilden contest of 1876.
<br>  
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;While the Electoral College system is denounced as an archaic and anachronistic holdover, to abolish it outright would require a constitutional amendment.  President Carter pushed to introduce direct popular vote during his administration and Ross Perot argued for direct popular vote in 1992; some states have also considered replacing their winner-take-all rules with the split-vote system.  However, until the Electoral College produces another untoward outcome, there is unlikely to be any sustained move to change it.
 <P>
Beyond the Electoral College formalities, what happens in the transition period obviously depends upon whether President Clinton is re-elected or not.  Should Clinton gain a second term, one may see actions designed to convey a sense of renewed activity.  Possibilities might be a Cabinet re-shuffle or a mega-event comparable to his 1992 Economic Conference.  Planning and preparations for the inaugural will begin.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;Should President Clinton be defeated, the new president-elect and his team must make effective use of the roughly seventy-five days until the inauguration.  Expectations are high.  The one-time candidate must assume a "presidential" aura, and, amid euphoria and exhaustion, responsibility looms.  Charles Jones, a visiting fellow at the Brookings Institution, says that the campaign revolves around one person, the candidate; afterwards the challenge is "attaching that person to the government."  The president-elect and the transition team make crucial decisions about personnel, policy and logistics.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;A certain amount of tension in this period is inevitable.  People who have worked hard on the campaign now see others being brought in to manage the transition.  There is much jockeying for position, and resumes proliferate.
<br>
&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;&#160;While the business of creating or re-forming an administration proceeds, preparations for the ceremonial side of the transfer of power are underway.  Inaugurals are exercises rich in symbolism.  From a practical standpoint, the Inaugural Committee also can be a good place to put some of the former campaign people.  Several days of inaugural festivities lead up to noon on January 20, 1997, when the oath of office will be administered.
<P>

<b>Additional Resources:</b>
<ul>
Charles O. Jones, at the Brookings Institution, is working on a book <I>On Becoming President: The Passage from Campaigning to Governing.</I>
<P>
James Pfiffner.  1988.  <I>The Strategic Presidency: Hitting the Ground Running</I>.  Chicago: The Dorsey Press.  (new edition scheduled in 1996)
<P>
Walter Berns, ed.  1992.  <I>After the People Vote: A Guide to the Electoral College:</I> Revised and Enlarged Edition.  Washington, DC: AEI Press.
<P>
