<html><head><title>VOTE AMERICA:  Images</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2>Images</h2>
</center>
<P>
Modern politics revolves around good visuals.  On many days, fleeting
images on television or a quick glance at the front page of the
newspaper may be all the information we get about the campaign.
 A candidate who holds up a chart or chooses a symbolic setting
to deliver a speech stands a better chance of catching the media's
attention--and yours.  While style alone cannot sell a message
lacking in substance, it can significantly boost a message's effectiveness.
<P>
If you go to a campaign event in person, your impressions of that
event may bear little connection to the mediated reality presented
in the nightly news or in the next day's newspaper.  Factors such
as camera work, editing, and the context in which the images appear
all combine to create a new reality.  Hans Kepplinger, an academic,
has in the past few years devised a &quot;model of presentation
impacts&quot; which provides a useful tool for understanding and
analyzing mediated images.  Kepplinger argues that as a viewer
is exposed to footage of a politician over time he or she will
develop an &quot;optically induced stereotype&quot; of the figure.
<P>
<b>Examples and video clips available only on CD-ROM version.</b>   
<P>
<bAdditional Resources:</b>
<P><ul>
Kiku Adatto.  1993.  <I>Picture Perfect: The Art and Artifice of
Public Image Making</I>.  New York: BasicBooks.
<P>
Daniel J. Boorstin.  1992.  <I>The Image: A Guide to Pseudo-Events
in America.</I>  New York: Vintage Books.
<P>
Hans Mathias Kepplinger.  1991.  &quot;The Impact of Presentation
Techniques: Theoretical Aspects and Empirical Findings.&quot;
 In <I>Television and Political Advertising Volume 1: Psychological
Processes</I>, ed. Frank Biocca.  Hillsdale, New Jersey: Lawrence
Erlbaum Associates, Inc.
<P>
Herbert Zettl.  1973.  <I>Sight Sound Motion: Applied Media Aesthetics</I>.
 Belmont, Calif.: Wadsworth Publishing Company, Inc.
</ul><P>
<P>
