Last-modified: Monday, 29-Jan-96 23:16:17 GMT
Content-length: 3198
Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<html><head><title>Vitrual Entertainment's VOTE AMERICA</title></head>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="tile.gif">
<blockquote>
<center>
<a href="http://www.virtent.com"><img src="votelogo.gif" border="0"></a>
<P>
<h2>Statistics</h2>
</center>
<P>
In an election year the latest numbers on unemployment, inflation,
factory orders, housing starts, etc. are often hyped/downplayed
as evidence of the success/failure of government programs and
policies.  It seems as if a politician can find a statistic to
support just about any viewpoint, and for that viewpoint there
will also be a set of statistics that directly contradicts it.
 
<P>
Dr. David Murray, research director of the nonprofit, nonpartisan
Statistical Assessment Service (STATS), argues that some numbers
are better than others.  Data arising from studies that do not
follow accepted procedures and methodology should be discounted.
 An estimate is an educated guess and much depends on the assumptions
made.  Estimates can be derived from a close study of existing
data or they may be off-the-cuff flights of fancy.   
<P>
Statistics can be twisted in ways big and small.  STATS literature
observes that, &quot;Advocacy groups regularly use the media to
pollute the policy debate with misleading or invented statistics
about purported social and economic problems.&quot;  Bad numbers
are a serious problem in public policy debates as they generate
much confusion.
<P>
One must pay close attention not only to the source of the numbers,
but also to the definitions used.  For example, an article may
cite numbers of &quot;missing and abused children,&quot; &quot;missing
children,&quot; or &quot;children abducted by strangers.&quot;
 The difference between these groupings can range from more than
a million to less than a thousand.  Murray states that every statistic
is an answer to a question; the trick is to identify the right
question.  The bottom line with numbers is to look carefully at
the labels that go with them and then to consider the underlying
argument they are being used to make.
<P>
<b>Additional Resources:</b>
<ul><P>
<a href="http://www.proxima.com/stats">Statistical Assessment Service (STATS)</a>
<br>2100 L Street, N.W.
<br>Washington, DC  20037
<ul>
A nonpartisan, nonprofit research organization devoted to the
accurate use of statistical and quantitative information in public
policy debate.  STATS seeks to make journalists more accountable
for the statistics they report.</ul>
<P>
Darrell Huff.  1993 (reissue).  <I>How to Lie with Statistics</I>.  New
York: W.W. Norton &amp; Company.
<P>
John Allen Paulos.  1990.  <I>Innumeracy: Mathematical Illiteracy
and Its Consequences</I>.  New York: Vintage Books.
<P>
Victor Cohen.  1994.  <I>News and Numbers</I>.  Ames, Iowa: Iowa State
University Press.
<P>
Steven E. Landsburg.  1993.  <I>The Armchair Economist: Economics
and Everyday Life</I>.  New York: The Free Press.
</ul><P>
<br>
<center>
<font size="-1"><a href="welcome.html">Vote America Home</a> | <a href="order.html.cgi">Order On-line</a> | <a href="/townhall/">Town Hall</a></font>
</center>
<P>


</body>
</html>
