<CENTER>
<img src="/townhall/spotlights/2-5-96/96spot.gif">
<br><H2>Kickoff to Campaign '96: The Nomination Process Begins</CENTER></H2>

<br>
This week Town Hall presents a look at the upcoming caucuses and primaries that will play a central role in determining who will be the 1996 Republican Party presidential nominee. A front-runner will soon emerge with a tidal wave of support that should carry him all the way to the GOP convention in San Diego, and to the White House. Past experience has shown that success in these early events is critical to launching a successful bid for the nomination.<P>
For instance, no Republican candidate has has won the party's nomination in nearly a half-century without first winning the New Hampshire primary. The quick pace of the primary season is even quicker this year with the changes in the Louisianna caucus and the Delaware primary dates, and many of the pundits believe that the race will be over by mid March. The Town Hall spotlight shines some light on the small, yet pivotal caucuses and primaries of February.
<P><center><pre><b>
Louisiana	February 6
Iowa		February 12
New Hampshire	February 20
Delaware	February 24
Arizona		February 27
North Dakota	February 27
South Dakota	February 27
</b></pre>
<P>
</center>
<P>
