<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Guess the Bureaucracy:  Week 1</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/background.jpg">
<CENTER><H2>Guess the Bureaucracy</H2>
<h3>Week 1</h3>
</CENTER>
This Town Hall Spotlight provides you with the chance to learn a little bit about the organizations that run on your hard earned money--government bureaucracies.  

<hr><P>
<br>
<A HREF="1.jpg"><IMG SRC="1.gif" ALT="Photo of the Department of Agriculture" align="left"></A><a href="http://www.usda.gov"><h3>US Department of Agriculture</h3></a>

<ul><li>None of this bureacracy's employees stayed at home during the last shutdown; not because there were no "non-essential" employees, but because its fiscal 1996 appropriation bill had already been approved.
<li>Had budgeted $13 billion in fiscal 1996 ($434 billion over the next 5 years) for promotion of profitable US companies in foreign markets.  That's right:  your tax dollars are being spent to advertise for successful corporations.  Rep. Dick Armey called this "Coporate welfare of the worst kind"
<li>Its budget increase 881 percent between 1965 and 1995.
<li><A HREF="/heritage/commentary/op-ef7.html">Missing: $13.5 Billion --Heritage</A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/heritage/commentary/op-jf1.html"> Why "King Cotton" is Trashing Farm Reform -- Heritage </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/heritage/library/categories/enviro/bg1002.html">Freeing U.S. Agriculture to Take Advantage of the New Global Market -- Heritage </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/heritage/commentary/op24.html">Congress at Historic Fork in the Farm Road -- Heritage </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/govt-waste/CapitolHill/LettersToHill/mccain.html ">Letters to the Hill -- CAGW</A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/townhall/columnists/fume1005.html">ADM'S Ethanol Gets by with Help from Its Friends -- Fumento </A><BR>
</ul>

<hr width="50%">

<P><P>
<A HREF="2.jpg"><IMG SRC="2.gif" ALT="Photo of the Department of Education" align="left"></A><a href="http://www.ed.gov"><h3>US Department of Education</h3></a>

<ul><li>Since its creation in 1979, this bureaucracy's budget has more than doubled, to over $31 billion per year.  The vast majority of this money goes to fund technical assistance, clearinghouses, information, and specific (and often unpopular) programs, rather than to direct improvement of its claimed area of oversight.
<li>89% of its civilian staff (4,400 persons) was labeled "non-essential."
<li><A HREF="/townhall/columnists/schl0817.html">Let's Abolish the Department of Education -- Shclafly </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/townhall/FRC/fampol/fampol.html"> Family Policy:  1995 -- FRC</A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/townhall/FRC/podium/pd95f2ed.html">Disestablishing the Department of Education -- FRC</A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/townhall/spotlights/9-11-95/bennalex.html">Education Reform -- Empower America</A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/heritage/library/categories/education/cb7.html"> Candidates for Recission in the FY 1995 Education Budget  -- Heritage </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/townhall/spotlights/9-11-95/thomcolm.html">Thompson School Choice Column </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/townhall/columnists/schl0720.html">Education Reform, Ted Kennedy-Style -- Schlafly </A>
<li><A HREF="/townhall/FRC/infocus/if95d2ed.html">Out of their Own Mouths: Selected Quotations on the Significance of GOALS 2000 -- Heritage</A>
<li><A HREF="/heritage/library/categories/education/lect533.html">Heritage Lecture: Getting Gov't Out of Higher Education -- Heritage </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/townhall/FRC/insight/is95c1ed.html">GOALS 2000: The Case for Repeal -- FRC </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/townhall/spotlights/8-28-95/lamarspe.html">Lamar Alexander: On the Issues </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/heritage/p_review/fall95/thsack.html">College Sticker Price -- Fall 95 Policy Review </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/townhall/FRC/perspective/pv95c2ed.html">National History Standards -- FRC</A>
<li><A HREF="/townhall/FRC/perspective/pv95j3ed.html">Education Debate Needs to Focus on the Family -- FRC</A><BR>
</ul>


<hr width="50%">
<P><P>
<A HREF="3.jpg"><IMG SRC="3.gif" ALT="Photo of the Interstate Commerce Commission" align="left"></A><h3>Interstate Commerce Commission</h3>

<ul><li>It is the nation's oldest federal regulatory agency. 
<li>It has a current annual budget of approximately $5 billion.
<li>It controls how firms move into and out of the regulated sector, and ensures that the rates charged by those firms were "just and reasonable."  Major reforms in the early 1980s reduced the control of this agency over its area of oversight, and increased competition and lowered prices in the process.
</ul>

<hr width="50%">
<P><P>
<A HREF="4.jpg"><IMG SRC="4.gif" ALT="Photo of the Department of Commerce" align="left"></A><a href="http://www.doc.gov"><h3>US Department of Commerce</h3></a>
<ul><li>67% of its civilian staff (approximately 25,100 people) was labeled "non-essential" during the November shut-down.
<li>It is "a loose collection of more than 100 programs delivering services to about 1,000 customer bases," according to its own Inspector General.
<li>Its annual budget is approximately $3.6 billion.

<li><A HREF="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/lect536.html">Lecture 536: Downsizing Government, by Senator Abraham
-- Heritage </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/govt-waste/CapitolHill/LettersToHill/comerc1.html">Letter to Chrysler for Commerce Dismantling Bill -- CAGW</A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/sbsc/ct9-6-95.html">Keating Testimony:  Dismantling the U.S. Department of Commerce -- SBSC</A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/em425.html">Abolish The Department of Commerce -- Heritage </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/sbsc/tax-0895.html">TAX Watch:  First Step Toward Budget Sanity: Eliminate the Commerce Department -- SBSC</A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/bg1049.html">How to Close Down the Department of Commerce -- Heritage </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/heritage/library/categories/govern/gip7.html">Commerce Department Funds Blatant Lobbying -- Heritage </A><BR>
</ul>



<hr width="50%">
<P><P>
<A HREF="5.jpg"><IMG SRC="5.gif" ALT="Photo of Old Executive Office Building" align="left"></A><a href="http://www.whitehouse.gov/White_House/Tours/OEOB/Welcome.html"><h3>Old Executive Office Building</h3></a>
<ul><li>This building was constructed between 1871 and 1888 to house the burgeoning Departments of State, War and Navy (two of which now have their own buildings larger than this one).  It now houses assistants to the President.
<li>It has an excellent view of the White House.</ul>

<hr width="50%">

<P><P>
<A HREF="6.jpg"><IMG SRC="6.gif" ALT="Photo of Department of Energy" align="left"></A><a href="http://www.doe.gov"><h3>US Department of Energy</h3></a>
<ul><li>This bureaucracy was created by Jimmy Carter in 1977.
<li>Weapons production and environmental cleanup, rather than its original area of oversight, now dominate its budget.
<li>Operates the Naval Petroleum Reserve, a series of oil fields set aside by Presidents Taft and Wilson to assure fuel for the Navy as it converted from coal to oil.
<li>Has a prefunded payroll, running through December, which prevented any of its staffers from being furloughed in November.
<li><A HREF="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/bg1061.html">How to Close Down the Department of Energy -- Heritage </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/govt-waste/CapitolHill/PressReleases/energypr.html">Press Releases -- CAGW</A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/heritage/library/categories/enviro/em432.html">Time To Permit Oil Drilling In the Arctic Refuge -- Heritage</A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/heritage/library/categories/enviro/bg846.html">Securing America's Energy Future:  Heritage </A>
</ul>


<hr width="50%">
<P><P>
<A HREF="7.jpg"><IMG SRC="7.gif" ALT="Photo of Internal Revenue Service" align="left"></A><a href="http://www.ustreas.gov/treasury/bureaus/irs/New_irs.html"><h3>Internal Revenue Service</h3></a>

<ul><li>While responsible for collecting 98 percent of the government's revenues--currently $1.25 trillion annually--this agency has not kept its own books and records with the same degree of accuracy it expects of citizens. 
<li>Its financial systems are outdated and unreliable, according to the GAO.
<li>Between 1990 and 1994, funds due to but not collected by this agency rose from $87 billion to $156 billion.
<li>Its very existence makes every American dread April 15th.
<li><A HREF="/heritage/library/categories/budgettax/fyi75.html">The $500-Per-Child Tax Credit Means One Month's Food and Mortgage for a Typical American Family -- Heritage </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/townhall/spotlights/8-7-95/nst.html">Lugar Plan To Replace the Income Tax With a National Sales Tax </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/townhall/columnists/chav1207.html">Don't Underestimate Taxpayers' Intelligence -- Chavez 
<li><A HREF="/townhall/spotlights/lugar.html">Testimony by Senator Richard Lugar
In Front of the House Ways and Means Committee, June 8, 1995 </A>
<li><A HREF="/sbsc/ct6-6-5.html ">Replacing the Federal Income Tax -- SBSC</A>
<li><A HREF="/sbsc/ct5-18-5.html ">"The Flat Tax and Small Business" -- SBSC</A>
<li><A HREF="/townhall/spotlights/8-7-95/i-flatx.html">Town Hall Spotlight On Tax Reform </A>
<li><A HREF="/townhall/FRC/perspective/pv95a1fe.html">Making the Home Office Tax Deduction More Available to Parents -- FRC </A><BR>
<li><A HREF="/pff/amciv/ac-may-jun/ac695gn.html">Income Tax vs. Sales Tax -- PFF</A>
</ul>

<P>
