<HTML>

<HEAD>

<TITLE>Town Hall Spotlight:  Affirmative Action & The Million Man March</TITLE>

</HEAD>
<body bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/townhall/paper2.jpg">  
<P>

<CENTER><a name="intro"></a> 

<H2>Affirmative Action in Light of the Million Man March<BR></CENTER></H2>

<HR><center><a href="#Misc">Spotlight on the Million Man March & Affirmative Action</a></center>
<P>
In 1965 President Johnson signed Executive Order 11246, mandating "employers doing business with the federal government to develop affirmative action plans to assure equal employment opportunity in their employment practices."  Affirmative action was born.
<P>
  For thirty years affirmative action laws have been a source of tension between whites and minorities.  Some conservatives have even suggested that the Million Man March was not just a call for African-American solidarity, but also a wake-up call to the nation's leadership to deal with the real anger of African-Americans and redouble their efforts to end the "slavery" of assistance programs like affirmative action that suggest, as Shelby Steele put it, "somehow color, not our hard work, can bring us advancements."
<P>
  On 27 July 1995 Majority Leader and Republican Presidential frontrunner Bob Dole introduced the Equal Opportunity Act of 1995, proposing that, "...the federal government should not discriminate against, nor should it grant preferences to, any individual because of that individual's race, color, ethnic background or sex."  Will this be the end of affirmative action and the associated tensions?
<p>
This week, <b>Town Hall Spotlight</b> focuses on the Million Man March and the issues surrounding affirmative action.
<P>
On Monday, we focus on the Million Man March as a backdrop for our discussion of affirmative action.  On Tuesday, read President Clinton's report on affirmative action as well as some reponses to that report.  On Wednesday read two conservative approaches to restoring equal treatment in employment.  On Thursday, read conservative commentary on the Million Man March and critiques of affirmative action.  On Friday we bring you arguments for the end of "quotas."  
<p>
Please share your opinions with us any day of the week by filling out our affirmative action questionaire.  We hope you find these articles enlightening!





<HR>

<P><a name="week"></a>

<CENTER><b><a name="Misc">Affirmative Action In Light of The Million Man March</a10-23-95r></b> <br>

<a href="#intro">(Introduction)</a></center><p>

